The Game Theory of Modern Democracy: AI & The Prisoner’s Dilemma

In 1950, two RAND Corporation mathematicians formalized a game that would come to define the nuclear age. Merrill Flood and Melvin Dresher called it the prisoner's dilemma — a deceptively simple scenario in which two rational actors, unable to communicate, must each decide whether to cooperate or betray. The cruel elegance of the game is that betrayal is always the rational choice for the individual, even though mutual cooperation produces the best outcome for both. It is a parable about the gap between self-interest and collective survival, and for seventy-six years it has haunted every serious conversation about how humans manage technologies capable of ending them.
On February 27, 2026, the prisoner's dilemma stopped being a parable.

The facts are these: Anthropic, the company behind the AI assistant Claude, held a $200 million contract with the Pentagon that included two restrictions — the technology could not be used in fully autonomous weapons systems, meaning machines that select and kill targets without a human making the final decision, or for mass surveillance of American citizens. These were not radical positions. They are consistent with existing international humanitarian law, with the stated policies of most NATO nations, and with what the technology can currently do reliably, which is less than its most enthusiastic advocates claim.
The Pentagon demanded the restrictions be removed. Anthropic's CEO, Dario Amodei, refused. He wrote that the company understood the military makes military decisions, but that in a narrow set of cases, AI can undermine rather than defend democratic values. The Pentagon set a deadline. Anthropic did not budge.
Within hours, the president directed every federal agency to cease using Anthropic's technology. The Secretary of Defense designated the company a "supply chain risk to national security" — a classification that, while related mechanisms have been used against specific components from US-based distributors, had never before been applied at this scale to a major American technology company, and which had previously been reserved for entities connected to foreign adversaries. The designation means that any company doing business with the U.S. military must now prove it has no connection to Anthropic's products.
That same evening, OpenAI — Anthropic's chief competitor, a company originally established as a nonprofit dedicated to ensuring artificial intelligence benefits all of humanity, now operating primarily through a for-profit subsidiary backed by billions from Microsoft and Amazon — announced it had secured its own Pentagon deal. Its CEO, Sam Altman, stated publicly that the agreement contains the same two restrictions Anthropic had been fighting for, while also granting the military access for "any lawful purpose." Legal observers noted the apparent contradiction. The contract language has not been made public.

The prisoner's dilemma is useful here not as metaphor but as mechanism.
In the classical formulation, both prisoners benefit most from mutual silence. Both suffer moderately from mutual betrayal. But the temptation payoff — betraying while the other holds — is the best individual outcome. And the sucker's payoff — holding while the other betrays — is the worst.
Anthropic held. OpenAI defected. They took the Pentagon deal within hours, while publicly claiming to share Anthropic's red lines — taking the contract, paying lip service to the principles, and leaving the other player to absorb the punishment. In a one-shot game, the outcome is predetermined: the cooperator gets the worst possible result while the defector walks free.
But the analogy breaks in an important way that makes Anthropic's position more interesting than the classical formulation suggests. In a real prisoner's dilemma, both players face the same authority and the same consequences. Here, the authority — the government — is not a neutral prosecutor. It is an interested party that actively wants a specific outcome. It is not punishing both players or rewarding both players based on their choices. It is rewarding defection and punishing cooperation by design. That is not a prisoner's dilemma in the pure sense. That is coercion with a competitive lever.
And yet Amodei appears to be playing as though the game is iterated — as though it repeats, and reputation carries forward. The mathematician Robert Axelrod demonstrated in the early 1980s, through hundreds of computer tournaments, that in iterated games cooperation can be sustained. The strategy that won Axelrod's tournaments, again and again, was the simplest one: cooperate first, then mirror whatever the other player did. It was called tit-for-tat. It succeeded because in a long game, trustworthiness compounds.
The bet, then, is that reputation compounded over time outweighs the immediate cost of the sucker's payoff. If the political environment shifts — a new administration, a major AI incident, EU regulatory pressure — Anthropic is positioned as the company that held the line when holding was expensive. That has long-term value with enterprise customers, with regulators in other jurisdictions, and with the AI research talent pool, which is small and opinionated and which has already been leaving OpenAI over perceived mission drift.
There is also the possibility that OpenAI's confession is hollow. Altman's contract language is already being questioned — he claims it contains the same restrictions Anthropic was fighting for while also granting the military access for "any lawful purpose," and legal observers have noted those two commitments cannot coexist in the same document without one of them being meaningless. If that contradiction collapses, and the Pentagon uses OpenAI's models in ways that cause visible harm, OpenAI absorbs the reputational cost and Anthropic's position is vindicated retroactively.
But the stakes extend far beyond two companies. If Anthropic folds, every AI company learns the lesson that safety commitments are negotiable when the government applies pressure. If Anthropic holds and survives, it demonstrates that principles can be maintained under coercion. And if Anthropic holds and gets destroyed — loses enough enterprise customers to the chilling effect of the supply chain designation, cannot go public, hemorrhages talent — then the lesson is even clearer, and it runs in the wrong direction. Every future AI company will defect from safety commitments preemptively rather than risk the same treatment. The question is not whether one company wins or loses a contract but whether cooperation remains a viable strategy in the AI industry's relationship with state power, or whether the rational move becomes permanent defection.
This is the variant of the prisoner's dilemma that the political theorist and game theorist William Poundstone warned about in his 1992 book on the subject: the game collapses when the institution administering it is itself corrupt. In a prisoner's dilemma where the prosecutor rewards snitching, the only way holding works is if there is an audience — voters, courts, international allies, the market — that can eventually override the prosecutor. Amodei is betting that audience exists and will eventually matter, and whether that bet pays off depends almost entirely on whether American democratic institutions retain enough function to course-correct within the next two to four years.

There is a tendency, when discussing artificial intelligence and governance, to treat them as separate policy domains — technology over here, democracy over there, perhaps intersecting at the edges. This is a fundamental misunderstanding of what is happening.
AI is an amplifier. It takes whatever power structure it is embedded in and accelerates it. A well-governed democracy that deploys AI gets more efficient public services, better resource allocation, more responsive institutions. A captured system that deploys AI gets more efficient surveillance, more effective suppression, faster consolidation. The technology has no opinion about which of these it enables, and the governance alone determines the outcome.
This is why the Anthropic-Pentagon dispute is not, despite appearances, a story about defense contracting. It is a stress test of the only mechanism that could determine whether AI amplifies democratic governance or oligarchic control — and the mechanism is failing under the load.
Consider the current state of AI regulation in the United States. There is no comprehensive federal law. The current administration has taken an explicitly deregulatory posture, revoking previous safety requirements and signing executive orders aimed at preempting state-level AI laws. When states attempted to fill the vacuum — California, Colorado, Texas, and Illinois all passed AI legislation taking effect in 2026 — the federal government directed the Department of Justice to challenge those laws.
Simultaneously, a super PAC called Leading the Future, backed by the venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz and other major AI investors, is committing at least $100 million to the 2026 midterm elections, with the specific goal of electing a Congress that will prohibit states from passing their own AI regulations. The researcher Matthew Stoller of the American Economic Liberties Project offered a concise assessment of the spending: "what oligarchy looks like."
The companies building the technology fund the campaigns of the lawmakers who decline to regulate the technology, and the lawmakers decline, and the companies grow more powerful, and they fund more campaigns. This is not a slippery slope argument but a description of a feedback loop that is already running.
Three companies command roughly ninety percent of the generative AI chatbot market. Seven technology firms represent about thirty-four percent of the S&P 500's total value. Eight of the ten largest AI companies are run by billionaires. And the wealth concentration is accelerating — the ten richest American billionaires saw their combined wealth surge by $698 billion in the past year alone, a figure that dwarfs the GDP of most nations.
This is the landscape in which AI governance decisions are being made. Not in congressional hearings or public referendums, but in contract negotiations between companies whose valuations exceed the economies of mid-sized countries and a military apparatus whose political leadership has framed safety concerns as ideological obstruction. The public — whose lives, liberties, and constitutional protections are the actual subject of the dispute — is largely absent from the conversation.

What happened between Anthropic and OpenAI in the last week of February 2026 set a precedent that the AI industry will live with for years. The precedent is this: safety commitments are a commercial liability. The company that maintained them got sanctioned. The company that abandoned them got rewarded.
This creates a selection pressure across the entire industry. Over time, only companies willing to comply with any government demand — regardless of ethical implications — will survive at the scale necessary to train frontier AI models. The ones that resist will be designated threats, lose customers, lose investors, and disappear. What remains will be an industry shaped not by the question "what should AI do?" but by the question "what does the most powerful buyer want AI to do?"
The implications extend far beyond military contracting. If the template holds — if governments can coerce AI companies into removing safeguards by threatening their commercial viability — then every safety commitment in the industry becomes contingent. The guardrails on medical AI, on hiring algorithms, on financial systems, on content moderation, on surveillance — all of them rest on the same fragile foundation. And that foundation cracked publicly this week.

The fight as currently structured is about whether a private company gets to set terms on military use, and both sides have a legitimate point within that framing. The Pentagon is correct that a contractor should not have veto power over operational decisions — you do not want Lockheed Martin deciding which targets are valid. Anthropic is correct that current AI cannot reliably handle fully autonomous lethal decisions and that mass surveillance of citizens is a constitutional question, not a business preference.
But the framing itself is the problem. The question should never have been whether a private company imposes restrictions on military AI. The question should be whether democratic institutions do.
We solved a version of this problem before. When nuclear weapons emerged in the 1940s, the question was not whether the military should have access to them but who holds final authority over their use. The answer was not "let the contractor decide" or "let the generals do whatever they want." It was a codified framework: civilian control through the chain of command, congressional oversight of nuclear posture, international treaties, independent review, the two-person rule.
The framework was imperfect. It came terrifyingly close to failure on multiple occasions. But the principle — that weapons capable of catastrophic, irreversible harm require a decision architecture that sits above both the builder and the wielder — has held for eight decades. It held because it was written into law, not into contracts.
AI-enabled autonomous weapons and mass surveillance systems belong in the same category. Not because AI is a weapon of mass destruction in the traditional sense, but because the failure modes are irreversible at scale. An autonomous targeting system that misidentifies civilians does not offer a window for correction. A mass surveillance apparatus, once operational, has never in history been voluntarily dismantled.
The fact that a CEO's conscience is currently the primary safeguard against unrestricted military AI is not a testament to that CEO's character. It is an indictment of every institution that should have made his conscience irrelevant to the question. If the law established the guardrails, no company would need to fight this battle alone, no contract negotiation would determine the boundaries of acceptable use, and the Pentagon would not need to coerce compliance because the oversight would be institutional rather than corporate. Congress, the courts, international law — they have, by action and inaction, left a void that a single company is now expected to fill against the full weight of the state.
That is not governance. That is a system failure being narrated in real time.

The Hungarian-British physicist Leo Szilard, who conceived the nuclear chain reaction and then spent the rest of his life trying to prevent its use, once observed that the problem was never the technology. The problem was always the gap between the speed of technical progress and the speed of political wisdom.
That gap is wider now than at any point since Szilard's era. AI development operates on a timeline of months. Democratic institutions operate on a timeline of years, sometimes decades. The people who benefit from this gap understand it intuitively, which is why they spend so aggressively to maintain it. They do not need to win the argument permanently. They need only delay meaningful oversight until the integration is irreversible.
Every month without a legal framework is a month in which autonomous systems are deployed under policy guidance that a single person can rewrite. Every year without congressional action is a year in which the industry's political spending reshapes the body that would need to act. The window does not stay open indefinitely.
And yet there are fractures in the consolidation. The Senate voted 99-1 last year to reject a proposal that would have banned state AI laws for a decade, a margin that suggests bipartisan institutional resistance to handing the industry a blank check. The EU is moving forward with the most comprehensive AI regulatory framework in the world, with enforcement beginning in 2026. Anthropic refused to fold under extraordinary pressure and in doing so made the structural problem visible to millions of people who had not previously been paying attention.
The prisoner's dilemma is only a trap for those who do not know they are in it. The game changes when the players — all of us, not just the companies and the generals — recognize that the rules are being written right now, in real time, and that silence is itself a choice.
Flood and Dresher's original insight was not that betrayal is inevitable. It was that cooperation requires something the game itself cannot provide: trust in the system that enforces the outcome. When that system is compromised, the only remedy is to rebuild it.
That is the work — not a technology problem, not a business problem, but a democracy problem with a deadline attached.
